00:39:07,903 --> 00:39:08,143
Scott: Right.

643
00:39:08,223 --> 00:39:18,778
Scott: When they were new, they started out, you know, being, you know, arcade games, oscilloscopes, primitive computers, 70s, you know, 60s, 70s, 80s.

644
00:39:20,040 --> 00:39:26,879
Scott: And there was no way for those games to save anything other than the high score.

645
00:39:27,179 --> 00:39:27,380
Scott: Right.

646
00:39:28,481 --> 00:39:29,363
Scott: The high score list.

647
00:39:29,564 --> 00:39:30,005
Scott: That was it.

648
00:39:30,085 --> 00:39:33,715
Scott: A very small amount of storage because old computers.

649
00:39:34,517 --> 00:39:34,778
Scott: Right.

650
00:39:35,320 --> 00:39:35,460
Scott: Right.

651
00:39:35,600 --> 00:39:39,828
Scott: Nowadays, we're like blessed with amazing storage capacity.

652
00:39:39,848 --> 00:39:40,229
Scott: Right.

653
00:39:40,249 --> 00:39:41,672
Scott: We have SSDs.

654
00:39:41,732 --> 00:39:45,740
Scott: We got big giant magnetic spinning disk that hold terabytes of data.

655
00:39:46,101 --> 00:39:48,827
Rym: I got a 30 terabyte NAS up above me.

656
00:39:48,867 --> 00:39:54,960
Scott: We have cloud services like S3 that just have a ridiculous petabytes of storage capacity.

657
00:39:55,640 --> 00:40:04,260
Scott: It's like it's, you know, but in the earliest days of computing, storage was actually the most limited, most expensive, difficult part.

658
00:40:04,380 --> 00:40:04,520
Scott: Right.

659
00:40:04,561 --> 00:40:15,280
Scott: It's like you would get this computer, you know, had transistors or vacuum tubes or who knows what and what kind of storage, a magnetic tape that was really slow and could barely hold anything.

660
00:40:15,460 --> 00:40:16,001
Rym: Many times.

661
00:40:16,021 --> 00:40:16,682
Rym: Many times.

662
00:40:17,143 --> 00:40:17,504
Rym: Nothing.

663
00:40:17,784 --> 00:40:18,686
Scott: A lot of early computers.

664
00:40:18,706 --> 00:40:19,968
Scott: That held like a kilobyte.

665
00:40:20,188 --> 00:40:21,390
Rym: A lot of early computers.

666
00:40:21,691 --> 00:40:27,000
Rym: You would load programs into it via some means like a cassette or more likely.

667
00:40:27,340 --> 00:40:27,761
Rym: A paper tape.

668
00:40:28,021 --> 00:40:28,262
Scott: Yeah.

669
00:40:28,282 --> 00:40:29,024
Scott: With holes in it.

670
00:40:30,166 --> 00:40:36,420
Rym: And the best you could do is output to that same medium, which was challenging, especially in the early days.

671
00:40:36,681 --> 00:40:36,801
Rym: Right.

672
00:40:37,062 --> 00:40:37,803
Scott: They were slow.

673
00:40:37,843 --> 00:40:38,866
Scott: They were unreliable.

674
00:40:38,926 --> 00:40:39,929
Scott: They were cumbersome.

675
00:40:39,989 --> 00:40:44,440
Scott: They were, you know, go on YouTube and find videos of people like setting up super old computers.

676
00:40:44,981 --> 00:41:02,400
Scott: And like the whole beginning process is just like typing in a program by hand in order to get the computer to load a program from a storage device like a magnetic tape or a paper tape that can only be read linearly in one direction and not written to.

677
00:41:02,720 --> 00:41:16,800
Rym: It's like storage sucked on old computers, basically, which meant early games, early arcade games, that high score list, almost every old arcade game, if you unplug it, that list is instantly gone because they couldn't actually store them.

678
00:41:17,542 --> 00:41:17,662
Scott: Right.

679
00:41:17,682 --> 00:41:17,782
Scott: Right.

680
00:41:17,802 --> 00:41:23,720
Scott: So the storage devices were big, loud, cumbersome, slow and expensive for a long time.

681
00:41:23,840 --> 00:41:31,531
Scott: And therefore, any game that wanted to save anything would typically use what's known as SRAM.

682
00:41:31,591 --> 00:41:31,732
Scott: Right.

683
00:41:31,752 --> 00:41:37,300
Scott: Your computers today have DRAM, dynamic RAM, which if you want to know how it works, look it up.

684
00:41:37,901 --> 00:41:40,331
Scott: But static RAM is basically just flip flops.

685
00:41:40,612 --> 00:41:40,893
Scott: Right.

686
00:41:40,953 --> 00:41:42,680
Scott: Which is just a few transistors.

687
00:41:43,400 --> 00:41:44,204
Rym: You don't know what those are.

688
00:41:44,224 --> 00:41:47,700
Rym: There's an ancient episode of GeekNights where we explain what a flip flop is in basic electronics.

689
00:41:47,800 --> 00:41:51,359
Scott: You can also go on YouTube and probably find a thousand videos showing you what a flip flop is.

690
00:41:51,460 --> 00:41:52,365
Rym: The name is descriptive.

691
00:41:52,405 --> 00:41:55,320
Rym: They can flip and flop between states.

692
00:41:55,800 --> 00:42:00,690
Scott: One flip flop is basically a storage device that holds one bit of data, zero or one.

693
00:42:01,372 --> 00:42:05,200
Scott: And it's very small and you can have a lot of them and they don't use a lot of electricity.

694
00:42:06,321 --> 00:42:08,686
Scott: So in the earliest computers.

695
00:42:08,987 --> 00:42:09,207
Scott: Right.

696
00:42:10,670 --> 00:42:15,300
Scott: You know, you could flip flops were basically, you know, the storage device of choice.

697
00:42:15,420 --> 00:42:17,986
Scott: But there's still RAM.

698
00:42:18,507 --> 00:42:21,915
Scott: You still have to provide power to keep them on.

699
00:42:22,015 --> 00:42:24,200
Scott: If the power gets cut, they lose everything.

700
00:42:24,440 --> 00:42:32,580
Rym: So your RAM and your computer uses actually a surprising amount of power because it is constantly refreshing the data that's in it or it'll literally disappear.

701
00:42:33,341 --> 00:42:33,481
Scott: Yeah.

702
00:42:33,841 --> 00:42:51,520
Scott: But anyway, so the arcade machines and the NES games that had, you know, batteries in them and whatnot, they were using SRAM chips to hold some small amount of data in memory and remember it as long as the battery didn't die or the power didn't get cut.

703
00:42:52,141 --> 00:42:55,608
Scott: And then if if if the power was lost, that's a good buy.

704
00:42:55,648 --> 00:42:56,169
Scott: save game.

705
00:42:56,209 --> 00:42:56,389
Scott: Right.

706
00:42:56,750 --> 00:43:01,740
Scott: The only way to have like a more permanent save game was like the Famicom disk system.

707
00:43:02,161 --> 00:43:14,178
Scott: Or if you are PC gaming in those early days and you had disk drives and extra disks to save your save games onto, which were not cheap, were not easy generally.

708
00:43:15,960 --> 00:43:18,744
Scott: And it's like those that was not for most people.

709
00:43:19,344 --> 00:43:32,360
Scott: Most people did not experience save games until like, you know, the Super Nintendo, the Genesis, those both had some games also that use batteries and SRAM.

710
00:43:33,041 --> 00:43:35,987
Scott: So did the GBA, you know, the Game Boy a little bit.

711
00:43:36,067 --> 00:43:41,920
Scott: But real save games didn't really come about until PlayStation had memory cards pretty much.

712
00:43:42,441 --> 00:43:42,661
Scott: Right.

713
00:43:43,083 --> 00:43:43,684
Rym: Yeah.

714
00:43:44,045 --> 00:43:49,280
Scott: Though there was an era and the end PCs had and when PCs had more hard drives.

715
00:43:49,620 --> 00:43:49,801
Rym: Yeah.

716
00:43:50,121 --> 00:43:56,200
Rym: Though there was an era with especially cartridges like the NES, there were the games that had the little battery in them.

717
00:43:57,701 --> 00:44:04,379
Scott: Yeah, that's what I'm saying, that those are SRAM just saying yes, but you couldn't save that much on those.

718
00:44:04,480 --> 00:44:04,660
Scott: Right.

719
00:44:04,720 --> 00:44:06,065
Scott: It's like there was very.

720
00:44:06,126 --> 00:44:09,660
Scott: the amount of data you could save was very small and very limited.

721
00:44:10,060 --> 00:44:17,100
Scott: But case in point, Pokemon for the Game Boy had so much like compression technology going on so that they could actually save your game.

722
00:44:17,220 --> 00:44:21,891
Scott: And like you could, you know, it could remember what was in the PC and what was in which box in the PC.

723
00:44:21,971 --> 00:44:23,034
Scott: and what with the?

724
00:44:23,094 --> 00:44:25,760
Scott: you customize the names of your Pokemon, you nickname them.

725
00:44:25,860 --> 00:44:28,657
Scott: It's like they were pushing it to the limit with that.

726
00:44:28,898 --> 00:44:29,100
Scott: Right.

727
00:44:30,780 --> 00:44:30,981
Rym: Yeah.

728
00:44:31,101 --> 00:44:42,760
Rym: But NES games that did not do it this way had a way to save games by put by saving them on a physical piece of paper that you as a kid would write down a code of some kind.

729
00:44:43,121 --> 00:44:55,920
Rym: If you ever used a code to resume your progress on an old video game, that code was just literally what would have been stored into that SRAM if you had that in the chip.

730
00:44:56,480 --> 00:45:01,400
Rym: So basically it was getting you as a kid to save the game yourself.

731
00:45:02,641 --> 00:45:03,382
Scott: Yeah, pretty much.

732
00:45:03,843 --> 00:45:12,200
Scott: And it's, you know, when the amount of data that was being saved was very small and could be encoded in a clever manner, like the way Mega Man games.

733
00:45:12,280 --> 00:45:15,540
Rym: I was going to bring up Mega Man because I remember when I figured out how to give myself an E-Tank.

734
00:45:16,500 --> 00:45:17,643
Scott: Yeah, with the dot grid.

735
00:45:17,683 --> 00:45:24,280
Scott: Well, I just I just had from magazines and friends, I had the codes that took you to Wiley with full everything.

736
00:45:26,463 --> 00:45:28,039
Scott: But yeah, it's like, you know.

737
00:45:28,420 --> 00:45:29,263
Rym: But think about this.

738
00:45:29,764 --> 00:45:33,657
Rym: It's interesting because on one hand, a kid playing, you think, well, I saved my game.

739
00:45:33,717 --> 00:45:34,580
Rym: This is my password.

740
00:45:35,102 --> 00:45:41,100
Rym: But having mornosis, you realize that anyone who got to game to that same state would get the same password.

741
00:45:41,220 --> 00:45:42,203
Rym: It's not saving your game.

742
00:45:42,544 --> 00:45:48,440
Rym: It is just an encoding of a state of the game in on a philosophical level.

743
00:45:48,720 --> 00:45:51,820
Rym: Save games are just saving the state of a game.

744
00:45:52,321 --> 00:46:06,500
Rym: And the explosion of storage technology and computing technology got us to a point to where games could have extremely complex and persistent states that were not possible previously.

745
00:46:07,320 --> 00:46:16,740
Scott: Yeah, I mean, the capacity for saving a game actually created, you know, that technological advancement changed games themselves.

746
00:46:17,001 --> 00:46:17,161
Scott: Right.

747
00:46:17,201 --> 00:46:25,500
Scott: It's like if you couldn't save the game, then basically you had to design a game where where every time you played, you were starting from the same place.

748
00:46:26,241 --> 00:46:27,102
Scott: Right.

749
00:46:27,122 --> 00:46:37,780
Scott: And the game would be enjoyable to replay, even though you were always starting from the same place every single time and redoing whatever it was you were redoing at the beginning every single time.

750
00:46:38,580 --> 00:46:48,640
Scott: So you wouldn't want to make a game that was, you know, where all the good parts were at the end and no one would ever reach them or a game with like a lot of stories and chapters.

751
00:46:49,140 --> 00:46:49,240
Scott: Right.

752
00:46:49,260 --> 00:46:56,699
Scott: I mean, I guess you could let the player just choose their chapter, but it's like that means you're going to have to let someone just start on the last chapter if they want to.

753
00:46:57,681 --> 00:46:58,663
Scott: Nothing you could do about it.

754
00:46:58,683 --> 00:47:07,560
Scott: You know, you guess you could have cheat codes that'll bring up the, you know, various level selects, but that's basically the same thing as a password.

755
00:47:08,660 --> 00:47:22,660
Scott: So, yeah, once save games became a thing and there was more data that was able to be saved, games like Pokmon, all those JRPGs primarily were the first ones, I think, that really took advantage of having a long game.

756
00:47:23,281 --> 00:47:23,582
Scott: Right.

757
00:47:23,703 --> 00:47:28,398
Scott: Where, you know, you would start and, you know, where you left off Final Fantasy 1, whatever.

758
00:47:30,340 --> 00:47:33,367
Scott: And without that ability to save, those games are unplayable.

759
00:47:33,527 --> 00:47:38,800
Scott: Nobody is going to beat any of those in one sitting ever unless they're a complete wacko.

760
00:47:39,380 --> 00:47:39,480
Rym: Yep.

761
00:47:39,881 --> 00:47:48,379
Rym: I had a few games I liked as a kid that did not have any saving capacity and I was never able to beat them until emulators because I couldn't sit there that long.

762
00:47:49,340 --> 00:47:49,481
Scott: Yeah.

763
00:47:49,501 --> 00:47:54,412
Rym: What are you going to do, pause the game and just leave the NES on like all night?

764
00:47:54,432 --> 00:47:56,517
Rym: I tried that a few times.

765
00:47:56,838 --> 00:47:57,520
Rym: Didn't always work.

766
00:47:58,961 --> 00:48:05,820
Scott: Or even if you could, it's like, okay, but you get to the hard part, you got your one shot at the hard part, you try to do it, you fail.

767
00:48:06,481 --> 00:48:13,220
Scott: And it's like, okay, well, I just need to practice that hard part a few times, but to get another practice shot, you have to get through the whole game again.

768
00:48:13,761 --> 00:48:24,740
Scott: It's like, if you can save, at least you can load your save and just keep trying the hard part over and over until you get it and not have to keep redoing all the other parts every single time.

769
00:48:25,280 --> 00:48:25,361
Rym: Yep.

770
00:48:25,601 --> 00:48:31,094
Rym: Now this opened up a lot of the games that we like today, like a game like Civilization.

771
00:48:31,395 --> 00:48:33,540
Rym: Well, you're going to play that over weeks, possibly.

772
00:48:34,321 --> 00:48:36,050
Rym: You couldn't save your game, save the state.

773
00:48:36,311 --> 00:48:38,180
Rym: It's a game over, literally.

774
00:48:39,263 --> 00:48:39,354
Scott: Yep.

775
00:48:40,660 --> 00:48:52,140
Scott: It's hard to even think, you know, even today, games that are not in themselves a long game, they still end up having lots of things that you save, right?

776
00:48:52,320 --> 00:48:55,320
Scott: Unlocked characters or, you know.

777
00:48:55,420 --> 00:48:57,551
Rym: Well, look at the new Turtles game that we'll talk about in a future episode.

778
00:48:59,961 --> 00:49:01,860
Rym: It has a stateful and a stateless mode.

779
00:49:02,040 --> 00:49:06,940
Rym: You can play it the normal story mode where you'll unlock stuff and like there's some sort of progression.

780
00:49:06,960 --> 00:49:15,220
Rym: But you can also put it in arcade mode where it's basically, you've got X continues, X lives, it's completely stateless, go notched, it's just like the old days.

781
00:49:17,061 --> 00:49:17,942
Rym: And I appreciate that.

782
00:49:18,403 --> 00:49:27,180
Rym: Game design has changed a lot and I think there's a lot of things we can talk about in terms of how saving games and save states and all these things can affect game design.

783
00:49:27,260 --> 00:49:36,280
Rym: For example, a lot of games use the concept of you can only save at certain points, which becomes a checkpointing system in a sense.

784
00:49:36,761 --> 00:49:46,500
Rym: So like early Final Fantasy games, you'd often have a save point and then an arduous quest like get into that marsh cave, get the crown and get back out.

785
00:49:47,081 --> 00:49:50,491
Rym: And you got to finish that entire quest in one go.

786
00:49:50,511 --> 00:49:53,339
Rym: if you don't make it out before you can't save your game.

787
00:49:54,760 --> 00:50:02,820
Scott: Yeah, now some of that does, like you just said, stem from, you know, a good or maybe sometimes not so good game design concept, right?

788
00:50:02,820 --> 00:50:04,039
Rym: Because that adds a sense of peril.

789
00:50:04,500 --> 00:50:07,280
Scott: Before a boss fight and after a boss fight and whatnot, right?

790
00:50:07,720 --> 00:50:17,700
Scott: But also in not wanting to let the player, like if you just let them save whenever, well, they might, you know, be one bad guy, save, jump on a goomba, save and like slowly beat the game that way.

791
00:50:17,780 --> 00:50:27,660
Scott: But they also stem from a technological limitation in that if you let someone just save in any old place, right, it's like, well, that's a lot more data that you have to save in the save file.

792
00:50:27,840 --> 00:50:29,068
Scott: Like where did they save?

793
00:50:29,370 --> 00:50:30,899
Scott: What was the state of the game when they saved?

794
00:50:31,620 --> 00:50:39,220
Scott: And by having specific save spots, it's like, okay, you could have these discrete spots where saving happens.

795
00:50:39,600 --> 00:50:50,140
Scott: You don't need to account for situations where they might save in some weird spot or, and you can clearly encode like, you know, which save spot did they save in?

796
00:50:50,560 --> 00:50:52,184
Scott: They saved in save spot number seven.

797
00:50:52,225 --> 00:50:57,860
Scott: It only takes up one space in the memory to figure out where the character should be in the game.

798
00:50:58,441 --> 00:51:02,951
Scott: If you don't have that, well, now you need to encode the full location of the character.

799
00:51:03,011 --> 00:51:06,960
Scott: They were in level seven at this coordinate and this coordinate, right?

800
00:51:07,100 --> 00:51:11,567
Scott: It's, it might not be that much more data depending on the game, but it could be more.

801
00:51:11,928 --> 00:51:19,860
Scott: And it was very much at a premium in those early computers, you know, systems of how much data you could save.

802
00:51:20,341 --> 00:51:28,480
Rym: And nowadays there are basically zero technical limitations on how saving and suspending and all these different things work.

803
00:51:28,900 --> 00:51:37,360
Rym: So now anything you encounter, except in extremely esoteric situations are going to be game design decisions.

804
00:51:37,901 --> 00:51:50,800
Rym: And at this point, the intersection of game design and accessibility and playability becomes a very dynamic and changing and interesting space that we, there's no way we can fully cover in one episode of GeekNights.

805
00:51:51,220 --> 00:51:57,240
Rym: For example, some games, the idea of permadeath, let's forget the history of where it came from.

806
00:51:57,340 --> 00:52:05,120
Rym: So nowadays you can make a game where you can save your game, keep going, save your game, go eat dinner, load the save file, play again.

807
00:52:05,461 --> 00:52:12,580
Rym: But if you die, all those save files get deleted because you want the concept of permadeath, permanent death.

808
00:52:13,020 --> 00:52:14,428
Rym: Slay the Spire is an example of this.

809
00:52:14,468 --> 00:52:16,720
Rym: You can stop playing at any time and save your game.

810
00:52:16,900 --> 00:52:18,846
Rym: Like if you're busy, house is on fire.

811
00:52:18,887 --> 00:52:22,860
Rym: You don't keep playing Slay the Spire, like pause the game, save it and leave.

812
00:52:23,521 --> 00:52:27,248
Rym: But you can only load a save file once effectively.

813
00:52:27,549 --> 00:52:33,120
Rym: So you can't save the game, try something, fail, go back, load the save file, try it again.

814
00:52:33,821 --> 00:52:39,852
Scott: Well, except you can because if, you know, not officially, but it's just a file on your computer.

815
00:52:39,892 --> 00:52:44,540
Scott: You could go and just move the file, copy it and then copy it back into position.

816
00:52:45,420 --> 00:52:45,603
Rym: Exactly.

817
00:52:45,623 --> 00:52:46,720
Scott: Cheat, basically.

818
00:52:47,420 --> 00:52:52,235
Rym: And as well, we've always said, unless there's competition involved, there's no such thing as cheating in a single player game.

819
00:52:52,295 --> 00:52:53,920
Rym: So play however you want.

820
00:52:54,321 --> 00:53:04,240
Rym: That's why I do applaud the fact that permadeath type things still exist, because I think they do serve as a very interesting challenge, that an interesting aspect of parallel to games.

821
00:53:04,820 --> 00:53:08,125
Rym: But I like the idea that you can opt out of that.

822
00:53:08,646 --> 00:53:16,960
Rym: And since you could fuck with the game anyway by hacking it or cheating in some fashion, why not just make it an option that you could turn off in a single player game?

823
00:53:17,240 --> 00:53:18,278
Rym: And a lot of games do that.

824
00:53:19,081 --> 00:53:19,983
Scott: Well, that's true.

825
00:53:20,143 --> 00:53:29,460
Scott: There are some options, especially a permadeath option that, you know, games will let the player choose, because obviously there's no point in forcing that on someone.

826
00:53:29,520 --> 00:53:32,920
Rym: But if that game is a competitive game with a ladder, you can't do that.

827
00:53:33,541 --> 00:53:34,683
Scott: Well, maybe it depends.

828
00:53:34,783 --> 00:53:36,206
Scott: But here's the thing.

829
00:53:37,108 --> 00:53:39,173
Scott: You could take that argument even further.

830
00:53:39,193 --> 00:53:42,500
Scott: A save file is just data in a file, right?

831
00:53:42,540 --> 00:53:47,611
Scott: For example, I loaded up some old gold box D&D games on GOG, right?

832
00:53:48,352 --> 00:53:52,060
Scott: And it's just the save file is just a fucking file.

833
00:53:52,581 --> 00:53:55,687
Scott: So and you're like you're sitting there like rolling your character's stats.

834
00:53:55,868 --> 00:53:56,469
Scott: I didn't do that.

835
00:53:56,810 --> 00:53:58,975
Scott: I rolled up characters with random stats.

836
00:53:59,296 --> 00:54:01,320
Scott: I opened up the save file in a hex editor.

837
00:54:01,660 --> 00:54:04,418
Rym: Oh, look, suddenly 18 strength, 18 charisma, 18 dexterity.

838
00:54:04,418 --> 00:54:05,562
Rym: 18?

839
00:54:05,562 --> 00:54:14,320
Scott: You mean 99 strength, 99 charisma, 99 dex as the highest number that would fit in the file without breaking the game.

840
00:54:14,801 --> 00:54:18,356
Scott: Oh, let me just give myself all the best equipment and a million HP.

841
00:54:18,416 --> 00:54:19,179
Scott: And it's, you know.

842
00:54:19,320 --> 00:54:21,600
Scott: Thank you for saving us, SOH character.

843
00:54:22,860 --> 00:54:23,061
Scott: Right.

844
00:54:23,121 --> 00:54:23,441
Scott: It's like.

845
00:54:24,902 --> 00:54:44,380
Scott: so, you know, it's like trying to prevent if as soon as you have a save file in some way, trying to prevent the player from having full control over what's in that save file is just sort of like you're just taking advantage of their technological, lack of technological prowess.

846
00:54:44,741 --> 00:54:45,322
Rym: It is effort.

847
00:54:45,342 --> 00:54:55,420
Rym: Like if you're on a Nintendo Switch playing a game that has a permadeath option and you turn that option off, what percentage of people would bother to try to recover that save file?

848
00:54:55,460 --> 00:54:56,001
Rym: Well, if it's a no.

849
00:54:56,041 --> 00:54:57,724
Scott: But if it's an option, then there's no point.

850
00:54:57,804 --> 00:55:06,840
Scott: But if you're making a JRPG today, for example, I would argue that not only if you want let's say you want to have permadeath in your JRPG for some reason.

851
00:55:06,960 --> 00:55:07,681
Scott: OK, go ahead.

852
00:55:07,721 --> 00:55:08,763
Scott: Make an option for that.

853
00:55:08,803 --> 00:55:09,003
Scott: Right.

854
00:55:09,044 --> 00:55:14,713
Scott: But why not have also an option for literally everything that's in the save file?

855
00:55:14,753 --> 00:55:19,300
Scott: Let them choose which save spot they're at, which characters are in the party, what their levels are.

856
00:55:19,480 --> 00:55:23,310
Rym: And a lot of games do this, even if it's not super well documented with the debugger mode.

857
00:55:23,350 --> 00:55:27,140
Rym: A lot of games have a debug mode you can access in game if you know what to do.

858
00:55:27,320 --> 00:55:29,367
Scott: Give the give the players a save editor.

859
00:55:29,447 --> 00:55:30,451
Scott: Almost no one does that.

860
00:55:30,471 --> 00:55:33,060
Scott: There's plenty of save editors that, you know, people have made.

861
00:55:34,160 --> 00:55:39,020
Rym: Civilization games were notable in the early days that they documented all of this and encouraged you to fuck around.

862
00:55:39,840 --> 00:55:41,223
Scott: Yes, though very few.

863
00:55:41,324 --> 00:55:48,180
Scott: But the vast majority of games do not expect the player to even realize that save editing is a possibility.

864
00:55:49,741 --> 00:55:52,666
Scott: But it very much is pretty much for every save game ever.

865
00:55:52,686 --> 00:55:56,393
Scott: And I think that we should make save editing more accessible.

866
00:55:57,154 --> 00:56:00,140
Scott: It's like if it's a single player game, who cares?

867
00:56:00,720 --> 00:56:03,908
Scott: If someone was wants to see the game ending, it's like they could see it on YouTube.

868
00:56:04,229 --> 00:56:08,520
Scott: What does it matter if they used to edit their save file to see the same thing they could have seen on YouTube?

869
00:56:08,881 --> 00:56:09,441
Scott: Who cares?

870
00:56:09,922 --> 00:56:10,903
Scott: But yeah, there's a thing.

871
00:56:11,224 --> 00:56:13,107
Scott: Speedrunners use it a lot.

872
00:56:13,948 --> 00:56:19,616
Scott: It's called save scumming, where you basically use a save game.

873
00:56:20,237 --> 00:56:22,220
Scott: You intentionally save your game.

874
00:56:23,321 --> 00:56:31,260
Scott: And then you do something that can't be undone, usually to acquire information, like maybe in a randomizer game.

875
00:56:31,721 --> 00:56:36,109
Scott: So let's say you're playing Link to the Past randomizer and you have the mushroom.

876
00:56:36,310 --> 00:56:41,720
Scott: It's like, well, you could use the mushroom to give it what you're supposed to do with the intended use.

877
00:56:41,920 --> 00:56:47,920
Scott: You give it to the witch and you get a random item from the witch in Link to the Past.

878
00:56:48,820 --> 00:57:01,080
Scott: But there is a glitch in Link to the Past randomizer where if you have the mushroom, you can basically do fake powder and go to the magic bat and get the magic pat to give you the magic bat item.

879
00:57:01,340 --> 00:57:07,093
Scott: Even if you don't have the magic powder that you would normally need, you know, there's a trick you can do with the mushroom.

880
00:57:07,574 --> 00:57:10,060
Scott: But if you gave the mushroom to the witch, you can't do that anymore.

881
00:57:11,401 --> 00:57:17,276
Scott: So what you can do is you can save your game, give the mushroom to the witch, see if what the witch gives you is any good.

882
00:57:17,296 --> 00:57:19,000
Scott: If it is, okay, fine.

883
00:57:19,360 --> 00:57:26,620
Scott: But if the witch gives you some garbage, just load the save game, undo what you just did, and then go give the mushroom to the magic bat instead.

884
00:57:27,840 --> 00:57:36,577
Scott: And you're sort of somewhat cheating by saving, but it's part of the game because the other player, you're racing another person who's playing the same game and they can do it too.

885
00:57:37,018 --> 00:57:37,820
Scott: So it's not cheating.

886
00:57:39,701 --> 00:57:40,842
Rym: Well, never mind save states.

887
00:57:40,983 --> 00:57:45,949
Rym: And it's notable that, you know, that was something that only existed in emulators for the longest time.

888
00:57:46,309 --> 00:57:54,860
Rym: But like today on the switch, if you use the NES or the SNES emulator built in there, you can just rewind time and make save states and all the stuff that emulators use to do.

889
00:57:55,221 --> 00:57:58,847
Scott: So a save state goes beyond a normal save game, right?

890
00:57:58,927 --> 00:58:06,380
Scott: A save game is like the game itself has designed a system for saving specific data to load later.

891
00:58:06,860 --> 00:58:15,300
Scott: A save state is literally freeze the state, you know, because my computer has so much storage, I'll just freeze the entire emulated computer.

892
00:58:16,281 --> 00:58:25,700
Scott: All of its RAM, all of its everything and save it to disk and load it up later as if the computer was on the whole time, as if the NES was paused that whole time.

893
00:58:26,341 --> 00:58:31,580
Scott: And I can have as many of these save states as I want because my hard drive is enormous and I can load any one of them that I want.

894
00:58:32,181 --> 00:58:40,720
Scott: And it's like, so any previous game state that I have managed to achieve, I can rewind to that and basically beat any game.

895
00:58:41,341 --> 00:58:41,481
Scott: Right?

896
00:58:41,501 --> 00:58:51,020
Scott: Like you could play Contra and move forward an inch, save, move forward an inch, save, got hit, load, and you'll eventually beat Contra without dying even if you suck.

897
00:58:52,221 --> 00:58:52,682
Rym: And you know what?

898
00:58:52,722 --> 00:58:58,580
Rym: This is a perfectly fine way to play because one of the things that, again, this now becomes purely a game design decision.

899
00:58:59,100 --> 00:59:05,180
Rym: Some games have a sort of punishment where there are parts of the game that are hard to get to and are themselves hard.

900
00:59:05,521 --> 00:59:13,220
Rym: So you have to be good enough to get past the hard part and then you have even fewer attempts at the harder part because you don't always get there.

901
00:59:13,680 --> 00:59:19,220
Rym: But with save states, beat the hard part and then just try the harder part over and over and over again.

902
00:59:19,360 --> 00:59:28,419
Rym: So in a way, save states help players gain mastery of games by letting them micro-practice and target the parts of the game they engage with.

903
00:59:28,820 --> 00:59:41,180
Rym: Whereas in the old days or games that prevent this or don't include this as a game design aspect, you generally play the early parts of the game more often and the later parts of the game less often and are less good at the later parts.

904
00:59:41,820 --> 00:59:48,000
Rym: So, like in FTL, you don't fight the mothership that often on the harder modes.

905
00:59:50,461 --> 01:00:01,800
Scott: I mean, I think you'll see, you know, most games these days, the AAA games and whatnot that are long, they don't necessarily have saved because the save state of the game is so much larger because it's a more complex game.

906
01:00:02,040 --> 01:00:05,456
Scott: You can't load it and save it that quickly like you can with an NES emulator.

907
01:00:05,476 --> 01:00:06,179
Scott: It would be like instant.

908
01:00:06,920 --> 01:00:13,000
Scott: But they'll just let you quick save or full save and just make as many save files as you like and load them however you like.

909
01:00:13,100 --> 01:00:19,400
Scott: And it's like, go ahead and do whatever, you know, save as much as you want, you know, to get through this game.

910
01:00:19,500 --> 01:00:20,526
Scott: It's a single player game.

911
01:00:20,546 --> 01:00:23,080
Scott: You're going to get to the end somehow, right?

912
01:00:23,960 --> 01:00:32,060
Rym: I mean, I used to save, like in Half-Life 2, I used saving the game a lot like how I would use my fingers and choose your own adventure books.

913
01:00:32,481 --> 01:00:35,010
Rym: I'd see something that obviously looks really dangerous.

914
01:00:35,392 --> 01:00:37,419
Rym: I'd save my game and go fuck with it and it kills me.

915
01:00:37,741 --> 01:00:42,659
Rym: Then I'd load my game and either fuck with it more carefully or not fuck with it.

916
01:00:43,520 --> 01:00:45,574
Rym: Like, I wonder if that'll kill me if I jump in there.

917
01:00:45,594 --> 01:00:46,057
Rym: Save game?

918
01:00:46,218 --> 01:00:46,380
Rym: Yep.

919
01:00:47,920 --> 01:00:56,700
Scott: Yeah, I think some of the times, right, is like this, you know, the saving is used, you know, when something is like difficult or challenging and you want to learn it.

920
01:00:56,880 --> 01:01:02,880
Scott: But sometimes it's actually sort of, you know, allowing the player to conquer bad game design, right?

921
01:01:02,940 --> 01:01:06,237
Scott: There'll be something in the game and the player like doesn't know, right?

922
01:01:06,720 --> 01:01:11,300
Rym: Can I land on that platform is such a common terrible design problem.

923
01:01:11,320 --> 01:01:12,464
Scott: Right, it's like, can I stand on that?

924
01:01:12,544 --> 01:01:13,367
Scott: Is that fire?

925
01:01:13,688 --> 01:01:16,940
Scott: Does this item, you know, I have one ice item.

926
01:01:17,320 --> 01:01:20,440
Scott: If I use the ice item, will it make, will it work on that lava?

927
01:01:21,461 --> 01:01:22,766
Scott: It's like, I've only got one shot.

928
01:01:22,867 --> 01:01:23,549
Scott: Let me try it.

929
01:01:23,690 --> 01:01:26,280
Scott: I'll save, try it, and load if it doesn't work, right?

930
01:01:26,380 --> 01:01:27,667
Scott: Otherwise you try it.

931
01:01:27,687 --> 01:01:28,934
Scott: It's like, that was your one shot.

932
01:01:29,115 --> 01:01:29,900
Scott: It's like, god damn it.

933
01:01:31,481 --> 01:01:42,747
Scott: You know, and I think that's, you know, when you see situations like that in games where the player's knowledge is lacking and they're using saves to overcome that, I think that's a sign of a bad game design.

934
01:01:42,787 --> 01:01:47,340
Scott: Like you shouldn't have a situation where a player has to make a decision based on ignorance.

935
01:01:47,680 --> 01:01:48,784
Rym: The galaxy brain is.

936
01:01:48,804 --> 01:01:55,371
Rym: you design a game around that where the players want to take radical experiments, but you design the game where you don't have to save and load.

937
01:01:55,713 --> 01:01:56,920
Rym: It handles it more gracefully.

938
01:01:57,281 --> 01:02:03,715
Rym: Like Prince of Persia pioneered that rewind game design, that game mechanic, the rewind.

939
01:02:04,156 --> 01:02:06,160
Rym: I'm a big fan of the rewind.

940
01:02:07,080 --> 01:02:08,000
Scott: Yeah, rewind is good.

941
01:02:09,543 --> 01:02:09,804
Scott: Yeah.

942
01:02:09,844 --> 01:02:14,620
Rym: So, we've already gone on pretty long, but another aspect is tabletop games.

943
01:02:16,162 --> 01:02:42,780
Rym: On one hand, they intrinsically save themselves because if you just walk away from the table, barring a little bit of, unless the game is lacking something like a whose turn is it marker, or you have to make sure you leave the game at a defined point where you know where in like the turn order or the states of the game that are not determined by physical components are, then all the rest of the state of a tabletop game is saved by the nature of the fact that it's a tabletop game.

944
01:02:43,340 --> 01:02:51,848
Rym: But at the same time, that's a lot like RAM in that if something jars the table ever so slightly, it's destroyed and unfixable.

945
01:02:52,389 --> 01:02:57,625
Rym: We used to, I remember, occasionally take a picture of a game just in case so we could reset it back up.

946
01:02:58,107 --> 01:03:00,980
Rym: Rarely did we actually reset it back up, but we had the option.

947
01:03:00,980 --> 01:03:08,213
Scott: I think part of the problem is that, you know, even if you save the physical state of a game, saving a tabletop game has this mental state.

948
01:03:08,233 --> 01:03:09,640
Scott: Well, video games does too, right?

949
01:03:09,860 --> 01:03:19,680
Rym: Yeah, so like Civ games, if I pick up an asynchronous Civ game, I'm sort of in this cadence because I only play so many at a time and I remember what's going on because it's refreshing my brain.

950
01:03:20,201 --> 01:03:29,651
Rym: But if I go take a save game from when I played Civ by myself, I will be materially worse because I don't remember all the details of what I was going after.

951
01:03:29,671 --> 01:03:32,420
Rym: Like, was I going for like a campus in that district?

952
01:03:32,542 --> 01:03:33,700
Rym: What exactly was I doing?

953
01:03:34,040 --> 01:03:43,620
Scott: There's all this information related to a game that is not in the game itself, that is in your mind, your brain state, that is unsavable and you don't have an amazing memory.

954
01:03:43,861 --> 01:03:47,780
Rym: A lot of that is your strategy, things you remember other players doing.

955
01:03:48,300 --> 01:03:51,554
Rym: Like, wait, did Scott need a lot of iron in this game?

956
01:03:51,855 --> 01:03:53,020
Rym: or am I remembering wrong?

957
01:03:53,380 --> 01:03:56,460
Rym: Was I trying to corner the iron market to fuck Scott or did I have some other reason?

958
01:03:56,740 --> 01:03:59,520
Scott: This also happens in the single player video games, right?

959
01:03:59,540 --> 01:04:06,640
Scott: It's like if you're playing Final Fantasy 7 and you save it and you load it again a month later and you forget the plot, it's like, just start over.

960
01:04:07,261 --> 01:04:08,265
Rym: Oh my God.

961
01:04:08,746 --> 01:04:17,599
Rym: I, in Final Fantasy Legend 1 on the Game Boy, I walked away from it for like a year or two as a kid and I hadn't beaten it.

962
01:04:18,082 --> 01:04:19,840
Rym: I picked it up one day, I was like, I should finish that game.

963
01:04:20,301 --> 01:04:23,540
Rym: And then I load the game, I see my characters, I go through my inventory.

964
01:04:23,700 --> 01:04:24,360
Scott: It's the one with the tower.

965
01:04:24,680 --> 01:04:24,801
Scott: Yep.

966
01:04:25,945 --> 01:04:30,100
Rym: I didn't remember which direction I was going in the tower, like which stairway was what.

967
01:04:31,122 --> 01:04:34,620
Rym: And it wasn't obvious and I tried to start a new game to see, it still wasn't obvious.

968
01:04:35,060 --> 01:04:48,158
Rym: So I basically walked in a direction fighting monsters for a while and it took me like at least a half hour of play to figure out what direction I should be going in and what I was supposed to be doing next.

969
01:04:48,800 --> 01:04:50,800
Rym: Modern games handle that a lot better, thankfully.

970
01:04:51,040 --> 01:04:55,720
Scott: Well, I think what has helped those situations a lot now also is facts, right?

971
01:04:55,760 --> 01:04:58,920
Scott: Just go online and look up a, you know, a guide or something.

972
01:04:58,940 --> 01:04:59,880
Rym: Yeah, that used to not exist.

973
01:05:01,040 --> 01:05:17,400
Rym: Also a lot of games, like even Zelda games pretty early on started incorporating a character you can go talk to who will remind you of at least something in the forward thinking that you still need to do that you could go do to get you back on some track.

974
01:05:18,361 --> 01:05:18,682
Scott: Yep.

975
01:05:18,762 --> 01:05:24,760
Scott: Games have done quite a lot to try to help players get back into them after loading a save after a long time.

976
01:05:25,020 --> 01:05:29,540
Scott: But even if I loaded Breath of the Wild now, I'd still feel like, just start over.

977
01:05:30,201 --> 01:05:30,483
Rym: Yep.

978
01:05:30,965 --> 01:05:33,600
Rym: I mean, I load my save file now and I've beaten the whole game pretty much.

979
01:05:33,640 --> 01:05:34,624
Rym: Which has not much to do.

980
01:05:34,644 --> 01:05:39,240
Rym: But if I had a save file that was like halfway through the game, fuck, start over.

981
01:05:40,200 --> 01:05:40,982
Scott: Yep, exactly.

982
01:05:41,002 --> 01:05:48,280
Scott: So, you know, and then I guess we could, you know, there's a lot to say about saving with regards to multiplayer and statefulness MMO type things.

983
01:05:48,420 --> 01:05:52,480
Rym: The fact that civilization games cannot fucking do it for the like, I'm sorry.

984
01:05:52,720 --> 01:05:52,921
Rym: Right.

985
01:05:53,583 --> 01:05:59,868
Scott: And the only thing I really want to say about that is that, you know, saving is sort of integral to those games because they're about statefulness.

986
01:05:59,908 --> 01:06:02,440
Scott: There's this shared global state that you're all modifying.

987
01:06:03,082 --> 01:06:08,740
Scott: But I really wish that someone would make one that was sort of not stateful, right?

988
01:06:08,880 --> 01:06:15,680
Scott: Like imagine an MMO where you actually, you can't save anything and you, you know, it's like we have all these roguelikes.

989
01:06:15,940 --> 01:06:21,840
Scott: It's like you play the MMO, you start a new character, you play until you die, and then you start a new character and play until you die.

990
01:06:21,940 --> 01:06:22,743
Scott: But MMO.

991
01:06:23,285 --> 01:06:27,060
Scott: It's like, if that exists somewhere, I haven't heard of it, but I want to see that.

